{"source_key":"sha256-6823a6327108a2b7a04e65390fec5f92","record_index":17,"record_hash":"sha256:00407027bbea8dc1927ec2bebc8507e6ecee44d578db55bbdf1c44d71502db9a","timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:43:50.571Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 16a029\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1757\nOutput:\n# Session Association Risks\n\nThis note documents the brittle parts of connecting captured agent sessions to\nbranches, changes, commits, or pull requests. It is not an implementation plan.\nIts job is to keep the risks visible before we choose a design.\n\n## What We Want\n\nThe durable object is still the project-scoped agent session:\n\n```text\nproject\n  gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:*\n```\n\nFuture review or branch objects should reference those sessions:\n\n```text\n<branch/change/commit/pr target>\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nThe relationship should mean \"this session is relevant to this target\", not\n\"this session uniquely generated this target\". That wording matters because the\nreal workflow is many-to-many:\n\n- one session can contribute to several branches or pull requests\n- one branch or pull request can involve several sessions\n- a session can be useful context even before any code exists\n- a session can contain useful discussion even if no generated code is kept\n\n## Why Capture-Time Association Is Weak\n\nAssociating a session with the current branch while capture runs is tempting,\nbut the capture moment has poor evidence about where the work will land.\n\nWays this can go wrong:\n\n- The user starts on `main`, generates code, then creates or switches to the\n  correct branch before committing.\n- GitButler can have multiple active branches in one worktree, so \"current\n  branch\" may not describe the destination of each hunk.\n- The session may produce edits that are split into a feature branch and a\n  bugfix branch.\n- The session may only be planning or discussion, with no committed output yet.\n- The user may discard the generated edits.\n- The capture hook may run many times during a long session, before the user has\n  decided what belongs where.\n- Branch state is workspace context, not durable provenance.\n\nFor those reasons, capture should continue to store project-scoped session data\n[TRUNCATED]\nship.\n- **Undo and redo:** replayed operations can accidentally replay stale metadata\n  changes or forget them entirely.\n- **Plain Git operations outside GitButler:** commits, rebases, and squashes can\n  bypass GitButler's association logic.\n\nThe implementation risk is footprint. If every operation needs custom metadata\nedge handling, one missed path creates silent provenance drift.\n\n## Data Model Implications\n\nThe current direction still looks right:\n\n- keep transcript data on durable project sessions\n- use many-to-many relationship sets from branch/change/commit/PR targets to\n  session keys\n- prefer change ids over branches as durable anchors when GitButler has them\n- let branch and PR views union lower-level relationships instead of owning\n  transcript copies\n- keep stored relationships coarse until the UI and workflow prove where more\n  precision is needed\n\nIf relationship metadata is added later, it should earn its keep. Possible\nfields are `method`, `confidence`, and `evidence`, but those should wait until\nthere is a concrete reader or UI that needs them.\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- Which signals are strong enough to create an automatic association?\n- Should the commit UI ask the user to confirm suggested sessions?\n- Should GitButler track an explicit \"active agent session\" during a workspace\n  session?\n- How should non-GitButler Git operations be represented, if at all?\n- Should relationships be stored permanently, recomputed from evidence, or both?\n- How much uncertainty should be shown to reviewers?\n- What is the smallest centralized API that can keep association updates out of\n  every individual mutation path?\n\n## Cautious Direction\n\nDo not infer association at capture time.\n\nWhen this feature moves beyond the POC, start with explicit relationships and\nhigh-confidence GitButler commit or amend moments. Treat stored links as\n\"relevant sessions\", not exact causality. Prefer one centralized relationship\noperation over scattered set mutations across commit, amend, squash, move, undo,\nand branch code paths.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:43:50.571Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}